#: Game.Levels.MeetFin
msgid "# Meet Fin\n"
"\n"
"Welcome to the world of finite types!\n"
"\n"
"In mathematics, finite index sets like ¬ß0 appear\n"
"everywhere βÄî as indices of vectors, as labels for vertices of a polygon,\n"
"as positions in a sequence. In Lean 4, this finite index set is called\n"
"¬ß1.\n"
"\n"
"An element of ¬ß2 is not just a number βÄî it's a number **bundled\n"
"with a proof** that it's less than ¬ß3. This bundling is what makes\n"
"¬ß4 a proper type rather than just a naming convention. The\n"
"advantage: the type system enforces the bound for you, so out-of-range\n"
"indices are impossible to construct.\n"
"\n"
"¬ß5 is a *subtype* of ¬ß6 βÄî the subtype ¬ß7.\n"
"You'll see this subtype pattern again in later courses.\n"
"\n"
"In this world, you'll learn to:\n"
"- **Construct** elements of ¬ß8\n"
"- **Extract** their natural number values\n"
"- **Prove** when two ¬ß9 elements are equal (or not!)\n"
"- **Handle** the edge cases ¬ß10 (empty!) and ¬ß11 (singleton)\n"
"- **Case-split** to reason about all elements of a small ¬ß12 type\n"
"\n"
"Three warnings before we begin:\n"
"1. ¬ß13 starts at **0**, not 1. The elements are ¬ß14.\n"
"   (Why? Because the defining predicate is ¬ß15 on ¬ß16, which\n"
"   naturally gives ¬ß17.)\n"
"2. ¬ß18 is **empty**. There is no natural number less than 0.\n"
"3. Two ¬ß19 elements are equal when their **values** are equal βÄî you\n"
"   need ¬ß20 to access this fact (you'll also learn the\n"
"   ¬ß21 tactic later in this world).\n"
"\n"
"The boss at the end will ask you to combine all these moves in a single\n"
"proof. Let's begin!"
msgstr ""

