"Combined with the **separation fact** from Level 7 βÄî that no\n"
"¬ß8 image equals ¬ß9 βÄî this gives you a **disjoint\n"
"decomposition**: ¬ß10 is the disjoint union of the\n"
"¬ß11 images (values ¬ß12) and the singleton\n"
"¬ß13 (value ¬ß14). Part 1 gives **exhaustion** (every\n"
"element falls into one of the two sets), and Level 7 gives\n"
"**disjointness** (no element falls into both). Together:\n"
"¬ß15, disjointly.\n"
"\n"
"**Connection to induction**: This decomposition is the structural\n"
"basis for **induction on Fin types**, just as ¬ß16\n"
"is the basis for induction on natural numbers. To prove a property\n"
"holds for all elements of ¬ß17, you can:\n"
"1. Handle ¬ß18 as a base-like case\n"
"2. Handle ¬ß19 by reducing to ¬ß20 (the inductive step)\n"
"\n"
"You've already proved every ingredient for showing\n"
"¬ß21 by induction: ¬ß22 (Fin 0 is empty,\n"
"MeetFin L13), the decomposition ¬ß23\n"
"(disjointly), and injectivity of castSucc (Level 8). The\n"
"formal proof will appear in the Cardinality world βÄî but the\n"
"mathematical content is already in your hands.\n"
"\n"
"There are actually *two* decompositions βÄî the **castSucc/last**\n"
"decomposition you just proved, and the **0/succ** decomposition\n"
"from Level 10 (every element is either ¬ß24 or ¬ß25). Both\n"
"are structural tools for ¬ß26. When you build tuples in the\n"
"next world: ¬ß27 (adding at the back) uses the castSucc/last\n"
"decomposition, while ¬ß28 (adding at the front) uses the\n"
"0/succ decomposition.\n"
"\n"
"**Succ Injectivity** (Part 2): The value reasoning pattern βÄî\n"
"convert to values, simplify, omega βÄî handles injectivity\n"
"automatically. This property βÄî equal outputs imply equal inputs βÄî\n"
"is called **injectivity**. In Lean, ¬ß29 means\n"
"¬ß30. You just proved\n"
"¬ß31 (in Level 8) and\n"
"¬ß32 (in Level 9). You'll use injectivity\n"
"formally in the FinsetImage world.\n"
"\n"
"Here's your navigation toolkit:\n"
