#: Game.Levels.FinsetOperations.L24_DualDistributivity
msgid "You've proved the **dual distributivity** law:\n"
"¬ß0.\n"
"\n"
"Was it really 'the same proof pattern, swapping ¬ß1 and ¬ß2'?\n"
"Almost βÄî the forward direction was parallel (case-split, rebuild\n"
"with ¬ß3), but the backward direction required a\n"
"**nested case-split**: splitting on ¬ß4, then conditionally\n"
"splitting on ¬ß5. This asymmetry is the difference between\n"
"distributing ¬ß6 over ¬ß7 (needs one case-split) and\n"
"¬ß8 over ¬ß9 (needs nested case-splits).\n"
"\n"
"Together, Levels 23 and 24 show that union and intersection distribute\n"
"over each other in both directions βÄî this is the defining property\n"
"of a **distributive lattice**, a structure you'll revisit in the\n"
"orders and lattices course.\n"
"\n"
"**A deeper connection**: You proved both distributivity laws from\n"
"scratch using ¬ß10 + logic. In fact, either one follows from the\n"
"other via De Morgan's law. De Morgan *dualizes* ¬ß11 and ¬ß12,\n"
"converting one distributivity law into the other. This means the\n"
"two laws are not independent βÄî they're two faces of the same coin.\n"
"The proof-from-scratch approach is more instructive (it exercises\n"
"the logic directly), but the derivation via De Morgan shows the\n"
"structural economy underneath.\n"
"\n"
"**The duality principle**: Look back at the identities you've proved\n"
"in this world. They come in pairs:\n"
"\n"
"| Identity | Dual |\n"
"|---|---|\n"
"| ¬ß13 | ¬ß14 |\n"
"| ¬ß15 | ¬ß16 |\n"
"| ¬ß17 | ¬ß18 |\n"
"| ¬ß19 | ¬ß20 |\n"
"| ¬ß21 | ¬ß22 |\n"
"\n"
"The pattern: swap ¬ß23 (equivalently,\n"
"¬ß24, or ¬ß25),\n"
"and you get the dual identity. This is not a coincidence βÄî it's a\n"
"theorem. In any **Boolean algebra** (and finsets form one), every\n"
"identity has a valid dual obtained by this swap. Once you prove\n"
"commutativity of ¬ß26, you *know* commutativity of ¬ß27 holds\n"
"by the same argument with the roles swapped.\n"
"\n"
"This duality is exactly what the lattice notation ¬ß28/¬ß29\n"
"(Level 16) captures: the abstract lattice axioms are self-dual, so\n"
"every theorem about ¬ß30 has a mirror theorem about ¬ß31.\n"
"\n"
"Next: the boss, which integrates set difference with the\n"
"unfold-to-logic recipe."
msgstr ""

