#: Game.Levels.FinTuples
msgid "# Fin Tuples: Functions as Ordered Data\n"
"\n"
"You've learned that ¬ß0 is the finite index set\n"
"¬ß1, and you can navigate within it using\n"
"¬ß2, ¬ß3, and ¬ß4. Now comes the payoff:\n"
"\n"
"**A function ¬ß5 is an ¬ß6-tuple.**\n"
"\n"
"This is one of the most useful identifications in formalized\n"
"mathematics. A vector in ¬ß7 is a function\n"
"¬ß8. A sequence of length 5 is a function\n"
"¬ß9. The entries of an ¬ß10 matrix are a\n"
"function ¬ß11.\n"
"\n"
"The advantage of using functions instead of lists: the length\n"
"is part of the type. You can't accidentally add a 3-vector to\n"
"a 4-vector βÄî the types don't match.\n"
"\n"
"In this world, you'll learn to:\n"
"- **Build** tuples using ¬ß12 notation and ¬ß13\n"
"- **Append** elements using ¬ß14\n"
"- **Decompose** from both ends: ¬ß15 (drop first) and ¬ß16 (drop last)\n"
"- **Reconstruct**: ¬ß17 (from front) and ¬ß18 (from back)\n"
"- **Transform** tuples via function composition\n"
"- **Use** tuples as data: verify concrete computations\n"
"- **Prove** two tuples are equal using function extensionality (¬ß19)\n"
"- **Flip** equations with ¬ß20 for reconstruction proofs\n"
"\n"
"The central tool is **¬ß21**: two tuples are equal if and only\n"
"if they agree at every index. You already know ¬ß22 for ¬ß23\n"
"elements (two ¬ß24 values are equal when their natural numbers\n"
"are equal). Here, ¬ß25 says two functions are equal when they\n"
"agree on all inputs βÄî same tactic, new context.\n"
"\n"
"The boss at the end will ask you to prove two differently-described\n"
"tuples are equal, combining reconstruction from both ends with\n"
"extensionality in a single proof."
msgstr ""

