#: Game.Levels.FinsetOperations.L16_LatticeNotation
msgid "# New Tactics: ¬ß0 and ¬ß1\n"
"\n"
"Before tackling the main topic, you need two new tactics:\n"
"\n"
"**¬ß2** replaces the current goal with a definitionally equal\n"
"statement. If the goal displays as ¬ß3, you can write\n"
"¬ß4 and Lean accepts it because ¬ß5 and ¬ß6 are\n"
"the same operation. The goal's *meaning* is unchanged; only the\n"
"*notation* changes.\n"
"\n"
"**¬ß7** does the same for a hypothesis. If\n"
"¬ß8, then ¬ß9 rewrites the\n"
"hypothesis to use ¬ß10 notation instead.\n"
"\n"
"Both tactics work whenever the old and new expressions are\n"
"*definitionally equal* βÄî the same value, just written differently.\n"
"\n"
"# Lattice Notation: βäî and βä™\n"
"\n"
"In Lean, finset union and intersection are implemented through the\n"
"**lattice** structure. This means you'll sometimes see alternative\n"
"notation in the infoview:\n"
"\n"
"- ¬ß11 is the same as ¬ß12 (lattice 'supremum' = union)\n"
"- ¬ß13 is the same as ¬ß14 (lattice 'infimum' = intersection)\n"
"\n"
"These are **exactly the same operations** βÄî just different notation.\n"
"\n"
"**The problem**: ¬ß15 matches ¬ß16 but not ¬ß17.\n"
"When lattice notation appears, you need to convert it first using\n"
"¬ß18 (for the goal) or ¬ß19 (for hypotheses). After\n"
"converting, all the familiar membership lemmas work normally.\n"
"\n"
"You may also encounter ¬ß20 in place of ¬ß21 (lattice order = subset).\n"
"The same ¬ß22/¬ß23 technique handles it.\n"
"\n"
"**Your task**: Given ¬ß24 (intersection via lattice notation),\n"
"prove ¬ß25 (union via lattice notation)."
