"There is also ¬ß9, which normalizes ring expressions without\n"
"necessarily closing the goal. Use ¬ß10 when ¬ß11 alone\n"
"doesn't close the goal but you want to simplify the algebra.\n"
"\n"
"**¬ß12 vs ¬ß13**: You already know ¬ß14 from earlier worlds.\n"
"The distinction: ¬ß15 handles **linear** arithmetic over ¬ß16\n"
"and ¬ß17 βÄî it can use hypotheses and solve ¬ß18 or\n"
"¬ß19, but it cannot handle multiplication of variables\n"
"or exponents. ¬ß20 handles **polynomial** identities over any\n"
"commutative (semi)ring βÄî it can expand ¬ß21 and collect\n"
"like terms, but it ignores all hypotheses. Use ¬ß22 for linear\n"
"goals with hypotheses; use ¬ß23 for algebraic identities.\n"
"\n"
"**The two-phase pattern**:\n"
"1. Use big-operator lemmas to transform sums\n"
"2. Use ¬ß24 to close the resulting algebra\n"
"\n"
"**Your task**: Prove the square-of-sum identity for big operators.\n"
"First use ¬ß25 to eliminate the ¬ß26 expression,\n"
"then close with ¬ß27. The resulting identity βÄî\n"
"¬ß28 βÄî is the kind of algebraic\n"
"rearrangement ¬ß29 excels at."
